                    <marginalia_text>Vsurpator.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Usurper.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Tyrannus.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tyrant.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Techna[e] Regia[e], seu potiùs Tyrannica[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>His royal or rather tyrannical skills.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Tarquinij Mnemosynon: non publici, sed priuati Concilij celebratio. Vniuersalia Concilia magis popularia: particularia, 
                        magis regia. Reges Gallia[e] ta[e]debat parlame[n]toru[m], cum coeperunt grandescere. Multa[e] vtrinq[ue] cumulantur rationes, et autoritates, 
                        pro, et contra. Lysander stat ab eius parte, qui disputat acutissimo ense. Sed hoc argumentum valet de facto, non de iure. 
                        Ut sa[e]pè multa s[upr]a, i[nfr]a. Qua[e] polychresta est pra[e]monitio.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tarquin the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Lysander"/>
                    <location name="Gaul"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Tarquin's record: the widespread use of private instead of public meetings. Universal assemblies are more devoted to the people, 
                and partial ones more to the king. The kings of Gaul were tired of their parliaments when they began to expand. From both sides many arguments and 
                opinions are heaped up for and against. Lysander stands on the side of the party that argues with a very sharp sword.
                Yet that argument has strength in practice [de facto], not in law [de iure]. As many [examples] below and above frequently show. 
                And that is a highly useful forewarning.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Veteratoria techna pragmatici tyranni.
                    </marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>The wily skills of the pragmatic tyrant.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Huc Lex regia Romuli: huc iura Maiestatis: huc vnius, no[n] pluriu[m] imperium. Nec malè; si benè Rex, non Tyrannus. 
                        Si suis communiter consulat, non sibi propriè indulgeat. Monarchia non est confusum imperium, sed distinctu[m]. 
                        Et regis interest, singulariter / regere. Sed tam discretè, quàm distinctè valet regnum, politicis principijs fundatu[m].
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>About this point, see the royal law of Romulus; to this subject the rights of royal dignity; to this point the rule of one, not of many. 
                And this is not bad; if it is a king in a good way, not a tyrant. If he seeks advice from his subjects together and does not give in to his personal
                interests in particular. Monarchy is not a vague, but a clear form of government. And it is important for the king to rule alone. 
                But his rule is powerful in both a distinct and clear way when it is grounded in political principles.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>In populari, aut senatoria Repub[licae] educati, vix idonei censores regia[e] Maiestatis, nedum meri imperij; quale olim Persicum, hodiè Turcicum.
                        Nulla talium seu regum, seu tyrannorum tanta Apologia, quanta Cardani Encomium Neronis, enregium paradoxum. Quo nullus Machiauelli, aut cuius 93, politici discursus magis est
                        politicus, aut pragmaticus, aut aulicus, aut etiam areanus vllo modo. Huc etiam Augustini seria Neronis apologia, quod attinet ad sui imperij auctorem Deum.
                        L. 5. c. 19. et 21. de Ciuitate Dei. Quando res humanus iudicat talibus dominis dignas. Talia multa politico maturè consideranda: quicquid effutiunt neosophista[e].
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Girolamo Cardano"/>
                    <person name="Nero"/>
                    <person name="Machiavelli"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <book title="Encomium Neronis"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
